{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782382746628,"sessionID":"ses_101b8caf5ffeN4H3YS4hZhe6E8","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"tool_Qei1v2eJqXVbLIe6vNxXFGDT","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/001-corpus-research/research/lineages/kimi27/deep-research-dashboard.md","content":"# Deep Research Dashboard — kimi27 lineage\n\n## Iteration Table\n\n| run | focus | newInfoRatio | findings count | status |\n| --- | ----- | ------------ | -------------- | ------ |\n\n## Question Status\n\n0/5 answered\n\n## Trend\n\nNo iterations yet.\n\n## Dead Ends\n\nNone.\n\n## Blocked Stops\n\nNone.\n\n## Next Focus\n\nIteration 1: Survey the `designer-skills-main` 9-plugin taxonomy and the standalone doc titles to build a coarse candidate taxonomy.\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/001-corpus-research/research/lineages/kimi27/deep-research-dashboard.md","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":".opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/001-corpus-research/research/lineages/kimi27/deep-research-dashboard.md","time":{"start":1782382746618,"end":1782382746625}},"id":"prt_efe4a51d3001W0YpRqdvlRnMhl","sessionID":"ses_101b8caf5ffeN4H3YS4hZhe6E8","messageID":"msg_efe49c9c4001c0wZuTeuZWET16"}}
{"type":"step_finish","timestamp":1782382747626,"sessionID":"ses_101b8caf5ffeN4H3YS4hZhe6E8","part":{"id":"prt_efe4a5fe5001S7X7d7ON9Hle5E","reason":"tool-calls","snapshot":"5778531ac27e9ffd8451896bc5f4bea314fe74e7","messageID":"msg_efe49c9c4001c0wZuTeuZWET16","sessionID":"ses_101b8caf5ffeN4H3YS4hZhe6E8","type":"step-finish","tokens":{"total":110135,"input":133,"output":1970,"reasoning":0,"cache":{"write":0,"read":108032}},"cost":0}}
{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1782382751942,"sessionID":"ses_101b8caf5ffeN4H3YS4hZhe6E8","part":{"id":"prt_efe4a70c20013Ir42H0es6BVbO","messageID":"msg_efe4a61d0001rA4rYg3cesNpIr","sessionID":"ses_101b8caf5ffeN4H3YS4hZhe6E8","snapshot":"5778531ac27e9ffd8451896bc5f4bea314fe74e7","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782382759532,"sessionID":"ses_101b8caf5ffeN4H3YS4hZhe6E8","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"tool_zGOUtfk6t9eLzF5Cg29cRRSx","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/ui-design/skills/color-system/SKILL.md","limit":80},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/ui-design/skills/color-system/SKILL.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: name: color-system\n3: description: Build a comprehensive color system with palette generation, semantic mapping, and accessibility compliance.\n4: ---\n5: # Color System\n6: You are an expert in building systematic, accessible color palettes for digital products.\n7: ## What You Do\n8: You create comprehensive color systems with raw palettes, semantic mapping, and accessibility compliance.\n9: ## Color System Layers\n10: ### 1. Brand Palette\n11: Primary, secondary, and accent colors with full tonal scales (50-950 or equivalent).\n12: ### 2. Neutral Palette\n13: Gray scale for text, backgrounds, borders, and surfaces.\n14: ### 3. Semantic Colors\n15: - Success (green), warning (amber), error (red), info (blue)\n16: - Each with background, foreground, border, and icon variants\n17: ### 4. Extended Palette\n18: Data visualization colors, illustration colors, gradient definitions.\n19: ## Accessibility Requirements\n20: - Text on backgrounds: minimum 4.5:1 contrast (AA) or 7:1 (AAA)\n21: - Large text: minimum 3:1\n22: - UI components: minimum 3:1 against adjacent colors\n23: - Don't rely on color alone to convey meaning\n24: ## Color Relationships\n25: - Tint/shade scales for each hue\n26: - Complementary pairs for contrast\n27: - Analogous sets for harmony\n28: - Neutral pairings for text/surface combinations\n29: ## Best Practices\n30: - Generate full tonal scales, not just single swatches\n31: - Test every foreground/background combination for contrast\n32: - Provide usage guidance for each color\n33: - Design for color blindness (test with simulators)\n34: - Include dark mode mappings from the start\n\n(End of file - total 34 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\nname: color-system\ndescription: Build a comprehensive color system with palette generation, semantic mapping, and accessibility compliance.\n---\n# Color System\nYou are an expert in building systematic, accessible color palettes for digital products.\n## What You Do\nYou create comprehensive color systems with raw palettes, semantic mapping, and accessibility compliance.\n## Color System Layers\n### 1. Brand Palette\nPrimary, secondary, and accent colors with full tonal scales (50-950 or equivalent).\n### 2. Neutral Palette\nGray scale for text, backgrounds, borders, and surfaces.\n### 3. Semantic Colors\n- Success (green), warning (amber), error (red), info (blue)\n- Each with background, foreground, border, and icon variants\n### 4. Extended Palette\nData visualization colors, illustration colors, gradient definitions.\n## Accessibility Requirements\n- Text on backgrounds: minimum 4.5:1 contrast (AA) or 7:1 (AAA)","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/ui-design/skills/color-system/SKILL.md","text":"---\nname: color-system\ndescription: Build a comprehensive color system with palette generation, semantic mapping, and accessibility compliance.\n---\n# Color System\nYou are an expert in building systematic, accessible color palettes for digital products.\n## What You Do\nYou create comprehensive color systems with raw palettes, semantic mapping, and accessibility compliance.\n## Color System Layers\n### 1. Brand Palette\nPrimary, secondary, and accent colors with full tonal scales (50-950 or equivalent).\n### 2. Neutral Palette\nGray scale for text, backgrounds, borders, and surfaces.\n### 3. Semantic Colors\n- Success (green), warning (amber), error (red), info (blue)\n- Each with background, foreground, border, and icon variants\n### 4. Extended Palette\nData visualization colors, illustration colors, gradient definitions.\n## Accessibility Requirements\n- Text on backgrounds: minimum 4.5:1 contrast (AA) or 7:1 (AAA)\n- Large text: minimum 3:1\n- UI components: minimum 3:1 against adjacent colors\n- Don't rely on color alone to convey meaning\n## Color Relationships\n- Tint/shade scales for each hue\n- Complementary pairs for contrast\n- Analogous sets for harmony\n- Neutral pairings for text/surface combinations\n## Best Practices\n- Generate full tonal scales, not just single swatches\n- Test every foreground/background combination for contrast\n- Provide usage guidance for each color\n- Design for color blindness (test with simulators)\n- Include dark mode mappings from the start","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":34,"totalLines":34,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/ui-design/skills/color-system/SKILL.md","time":{"start":1782382759520,"end":1782382759530}},"id":"prt_efe4a8aee001BELiF7hN4VYqZC","sessionID":"ses_101b8caf5ffeN4H3YS4hZhe6E8","messageID":"msg_efe4a61d0001rA4rYg3cesNpIr"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782382760755,"sessionID":"ses_101b8caf5ffeN4H3YS4hZhe6E8","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"tool_TSVk6Y9s70y7fH7xy6LdZBzd","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/ui-design/skills/typography-scale/SKILL.md","limit":80},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/ui-design/skills/typography-scale/SKILL.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: name: typography-scale\n3: description: Create a modular typography scale with size, weight, and line-height relationships.\n4: ---\n5: # Typography Scale\n6: You are an expert in typographic systems for digital interfaces.\n7: ## What You Do\n8: You create modular typography scales that ensure readable, harmonious, and consistent text across a product.\n9: ## Scale Components\n10: ### Size Scale\n11: Based on a ratio (e.g., 1.25 major third, 1.333 perfect fourth):\n12: - Caption: 12px\n13: - Body small: 14px\n14: - Body: 16px (base)\n15: - Subheading: 20px\n16: - Heading 3: 24px\n17: - Heading 2: 32px\n18: - Heading 1: 40px\n19: - Display: 48-64px\n20: ### Weight Scale\n21: Regular (400), Medium (500), Semibold (600), Bold (700).\n22: ### Line Height\n23: - Tight: 1.2 (headings)\n24: - Normal: 1.5 (body text)\n25: - Relaxed: 1.75 (long-form reading)\n26: ### Letter Spacing\n27: - Tight: -0.02em (large headings)\n28: - Normal: 0 (body)\n29: - Wide: 0.05em (uppercase labels, captions)\n30: ## Font Pairing\n31: - Primary: UI and body text\n32: - Secondary: headings or editorial (optional)\n33: - Mono: code, data, technical content\n34: ## Responsive Typography\n35: - Scale down heading sizes on mobile\n36: - Maintain body size (16px minimum for readability)\n37: - Adjust line lengths (45-75 characters optimal)\n38: ## Best Practices\n39: - Use a mathematical ratio for harmony\n40: - Limit to 4-5 sizes in regular use\n41: - Ensure body text is minimum 16px\n42: - Test with real content, not lorem ipsum\n43: - Document usage rules for each style\n\n(End of file - total 43 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\nname: typography-scale\ndescription: Create a modular typography scale with size, weight, and line-height relationships.\n---\n# Typography Scale\nYou are an expert in typographic systems for digital interfaces.\n## What You Do\nYou create modular typography scales that ensure readable, harmonious, and consistent text across a product.\n## Scale Components\n### Size Scale\nBased on a ratio (e.g., 1.25 major third, 1.333 perfect fourth):\n- Caption: 12px\n- Body small: 14px\n- Body: 16px (base)\n- Subheading: 20px\n- Heading 3: 24px\n- Heading 2: 32px\n- Heading 1: 40px\n- Display: 48-64px\n### Weight Scale","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/ui-design/skills/typography-scale/SKILL.md","text":"---\nname: typography-scale\ndescription: Create a modular typography scale with size, weight, and line-height relationships.\n---\n# Typography Scale\nYou are an expert in typographic systems for digital interfaces.\n## What You Do\nYou create modular typography scales that ensure readable, harmonious, and consistent text across a product.\n## Scale Components\n### Size Scale\nBased on a ratio (e.g., 1.25 major third, 1.333 perfect fourth):\n- Caption: 12px\n- Body small: 14px\n- Body: 16px (base)\n- Subheading: 20px\n- Heading 3: 24px\n- Heading 2: 32px\n- Heading 1: 40px\n- Display: 48-64px\n### Weight Scale\nRegular (400), Medium (500), Semibold (600), Bold (700).\n### Line Height\n- Tight: 1.2 (headings)\n- Normal: 1.5 (body text)\n- Relaxed: 1.75 (long-form reading)\n### Letter Spacing\n- Tight: -0.02em (large headings)\n- Normal: 0 (body)\n- Wide: 0.05em (uppercase labels, captions)\n## Font Pairing\n- Primary: UI and body text\n- Secondary: headings or editorial (optional)\n- Mono: code, data, technical content\n## Responsive Typography\n- Scale down heading sizes on mobile\n- Maintain body size (16px minimum for readability)\n- Adjust line lengths (45-75 characters optimal)\n## Best Practices\n- Use a mathematical ratio for harmony\n- Limit to 4-5 sizes in regular use\n- Ensure body text is minimum 16px\n- Test with real content, not lorem ipsum\n- Document usage rules for each style","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":43,"totalLines":43,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/ui-design/skills/typography-scale/SKILL.md","time":{"start":1782382760746,"end":1782382760753}},"id":"prt_efe4a8e61001en4gmIlzOobSUO","sessionID":"ses_101b8caf5ffeN4H3YS4hZhe6E8","messageID":"msg_efe4a61d0001rA4rYg3cesNpIr"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782382762189,"sessionID":"ses_101b8caf5ffeN4H3YS4hZhe6E8","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"tool_4IEUk9rpKerUxKAuUnL9aRLU","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/ui-design/skills/layout-grid/SKILL.md","limit":80},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/ui-design/skills/layout-grid/SKILL.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: name: layout-grid\n3: description: Define responsive layout grid systems with columns, gutters, margins, and breakpoint behavior.\n4: ---\n5: # Layout Grid\n6: You are an expert in layout grid systems for digital product design.\n7: ## What You Do\n8: You define responsive grid systems that create consistent, flexible page layouts across breakpoints.\n9: ## Grid Anatomy\n10: - **Columns**: Typically 4 (mobile), 8 (tablet), 12 (desktop)\n11: - **Gutters**: Space between columns (16px, 24px, or 32px typical)\n12: - **Margins**: Outer page margins (16px mobile, 24-48px desktop)\n13: - **Breakpoints**: Points where layout adapts (e.g., 375, 768, 1024, 1440px)\n14: ## Grid Types\n15: - **Column grid**: Equal columns for general layout\n16: - **Modular grid**: Columns + rows creating modules\n17: - **Baseline grid**: Vertical rhythm alignment (4px or 8px)\n18: - **Compound grid**: Overlapping grids for complex layouts\n19: ## Responsive Behavior\n20: - Fluid: columns stretch proportionally\n21: - Fixed: max-width container with centered content\n22: - Adaptive: distinct layouts per breakpoint\n23: - Column dropping: reduce columns at smaller sizes\n24: ## Common Patterns\n25: - Full-bleed: content spans entire viewport\n26: - Contained: max-width with margins\n27: - Asymmetric: sidebar + main content\n28: - Card grids: auto-fill responsive cards\n29: ## Best Practices\n30: - Use consistent gutters and margins\n31: - Align content to the grid, not arbitrarily\n32: - Test at every breakpoint, not just the extremes\n33: - Document grid specs for developers\n34: - Allow intentional grid-breaking for emphasis\n\n(End of file - total 34 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\nname: layout-grid\ndescription: Define responsive layout grid systems with columns, gutters, margins, and breakpoint behavior.\n---\n# Layout Grid\nYou are an expert in layout grid systems for digital product design.\n## What You Do\nYou define responsive grid systems that create consistent, flexible page layouts across breakpoints.\n## Grid Anatomy\n- **Columns**: Typically 4 (mobile), 8 (tablet), 12 (desktop)\n- **Gutters**: Space between columns (16px, 24px, or 32px typical)\n- **Margins**: Outer page margins (16px mobile, 24-48px desktop)\n- **Breakpoints**: Points where layout adapts (e.g., 375, 768, 1024, 1440px)\n## Grid Types\n- **Column grid**: Equal columns for general layout\n- **Modular grid**: Columns + rows creating modules\n- **Baseline grid**: Vertical rhythm alignment (4px or 8px)\n- **Compound grid**: Overlapping grids for complex layouts\n## Responsive Behavior\n- Fluid: columns stretch proportionally","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/ui-design/skills/layout-grid/SKILL.md","text":"---\nname: layout-grid\ndescription: Define responsive layout grid systems with columns, gutters, margins, and breakpoint behavior.\n---\n# Layout Grid\nYou are an expert in layout grid systems for digital product design.\n## What You Do\nYou define responsive grid systems that create consistent, flexible page layouts across breakpoints.\n## Grid Anatomy\n- **Columns**: Typically 4 (mobile), 8 (tablet), 12 (desktop)\n- **Gutters**: Space between columns (16px, 24px, or 32px typical)\n- **Margins**: Outer page margins (16px mobile, 24-48px desktop)\n- **Breakpoints**: Points where layout adapts (e.g., 375, 768, 1024, 1440px)\n## Grid Types\n- **Column grid**: Equal columns for general layout\n- **Modular grid**: Columns + rows creating modules\n- **Baseline grid**: Vertical rhythm alignment (4px or 8px)\n- **Compound grid**: Overlapping grids for complex layouts\n## Responsive Behavior\n- Fluid: columns stretch proportionally\n- Fixed: max-width container with centered content\n- Adaptive: distinct layouts per breakpoint\n- Column dropping: reduce columns at smaller sizes\n## Common Patterns\n- Full-bleed: content spans entire viewport\n- Contained: max-width with margins\n- Asymmetric: sidebar + main content\n- Card grids: auto-fill responsive cards\n## Best Practices\n- Use consistent gutters and margins\n- Align content to the grid, not arbitrarily\n- Test at every breakpoint, not just the extremes\n- Document grid specs for developers\n- Allow intentional grid-breaking for emphasis","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":34,"totalLines":34,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/ui-design/skills/layout-grid/SKILL.md","time":{"start":1782382762134,"end":1782382762187}},"id":"prt_efe4a932b001qe2QY7PYcIMeGK","sessionID":"ses_101b8caf5ffeN4H3YS4hZhe6E8","messageID":"msg_efe4a61d0001rA4rYg3cesNpIr"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782382763407,"sessionID":"ses_101b8caf5ffeN4H3YS4hZhe6E8","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"tool_cpymmcK6vWVM160hd0V14Ix8","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/interaction-design/skills/micro-interaction-spec/SKILL.md","limit":80},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/interaction-design/skills/micro-interaction-spec/SKILL.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: name: micro-interaction-spec\n3: description: Specify micro-interactions with trigger, rules, feedback, and loop/mode definitions.\n4: ---\n5: # Micro-Interaction Spec\n6: You are an expert in designing micro-interactions that make interfaces feel alive and intuitive.\n7: ## What You Do\n8: You specify micro-interactions using a structured framework covering trigger, rules, feedback, and loops.\n9: ## Micro-Interaction Framework\n10: ### 1. Trigger\n11: What initiates the interaction: user action (click, hover, swipe), system event (notification, completion), or conditional (time-based, threshold).\n12: ### 2. Rules\n13: What happens once triggered: the logic and sequence of the interaction, conditions and branching.\n14: ### 3. Feedback\n15: How the user perceives the result: visual change (color, size, position), motion (animation, transition), audio (click, chime), haptic (vibration patterns).\n16: ### 4. Loops and Modes\n17: Does the interaction repeat? Does it change over time? First-time vs repeat behavior, progressive disclosure.\n18: ## Common Micro-Interactions\n19: - Toggle switches with state animation\n20: - Pull-to-refresh with progress indication\n21: - Like/favorite with celebratory animation\n22: - Form validation with inline feedback\n23: - Button press with depth/scale response\n24: - Swipe actions with threshold feedback\n25: - Long-press with radial progress\n26: ## Specification Format\n27: For each micro-interaction: name, trigger, rules (sequence), feedback (visual/audio/haptic), duration/easing, loop behavior, accessibility considerations.\n28: ## Best Practices\n29: - Every micro-interaction should have a purpose\n30: - Keep durations short (100-500ms for most)\n31: - Provide immediate feedback for user actions\n32: - Respect reduced-motion preferences\n33: - Test on target devices for performance\n\n(End of file - total 33 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\nname: micro-interaction-spec\ndescription: Specify micro-interactions with trigger, rules, feedback, and loop/mode definitions.\n---\n# Micro-Interaction Spec\nYou are an expert in designing micro-interactions that make interfaces feel alive and intuitive.\n## What You Do\nYou specify micro-interactions using a structured framework covering trigger, rules, feedback, and loops.\n## Micro-Interaction Framework\n### 1. Trigger\nWhat initiates the interaction: user action (click, hover, swipe), system event (notification, completion), or conditional (time-based, threshold).\n### 2. Rules\nWhat happens once triggered: the logic and sequence of the interaction, conditions and branching.\n### 3. Feedback\nHow the user perceives the result: visual change (color, size, position), motion (animation, transition), audio (click, chime), haptic (vibration patterns).\n### 4. Loops and Modes\nDoes the interaction repeat? Does it change over time? First-time vs repeat behavior, progressive disclosure.\n## Common Micro-Interactions\n- Toggle switches with state animation\n- Pull-to-refresh with progress indication","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/interaction-design/skills/micro-interaction-spec/SKILL.md","text":"---\nname: micro-interaction-spec\ndescription: Specify micro-interactions with trigger, rules, feedback, and loop/mode definitions.\n---\n# Micro-Interaction Spec\nYou are an expert in designing micro-interactions that make interfaces feel alive and intuitive.\n## What You Do\nYou specify micro-interactions using a structured framework covering trigger, rules, feedback, and loops.\n## Micro-Interaction Framework\n### 1. Trigger\nWhat initiates the interaction: user action (click, hover, swipe), system event (notification, completion), or conditional (time-based, threshold).\n### 2. Rules\nWhat happens once triggered: the logic and sequence of the interaction, conditions and branching.\n### 3. Feedback\nHow the user perceives the result: visual change (color, size, position), motion (animation, transition), audio (click, chime), haptic (vibration patterns).\n### 4. Loops and Modes\nDoes the interaction repeat? Does it change over time? First-time vs repeat behavior, progressive disclosure.\n## Common Micro-Interactions\n- Toggle switches with state animation\n- Pull-to-refresh with progress indication\n- Like/favorite with celebratory animation\n- Form validation with inline feedback\n- Button press with depth/scale response\n- Swipe actions with threshold feedback\n- Long-press with radial progress\n## Specification Format\nFor each micro-interaction: name, trigger, rules (sequence), feedback (visual/audio/haptic), duration/easing, loop behavior, accessibility considerations.\n## Best Practices\n- Every micro-interaction should have a purpose\n- Keep durations short (100-500ms for most)\n- Provide immediate feedback for user actions\n- Respect reduced-motion preferences\n- Test on target devices for performance","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":33,"totalLines":33,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/interaction-design/skills/micro-interaction-spec/SKILL.md","time":{"start":1782382763390,"end":1782382763404}},"id":"prt_efe4a989d001YnDaT0xcw25heI","sessionID":"ses_101b8caf5ffeN4H3YS4hZhe6E8","messageID":"msg_efe4a61d0001rA4rYg3cesNpIr"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782382764915,"sessionID":"ses_101b8caf5ffeN4H3YS4hZhe6E8","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"tool_c4QfiKSZWwkqGJDLASQgR2co","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/visual-critique/skills/critique-composition/SKILL.md","limit":80},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/visual-critique/skills/critique-composition/SKILL.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: name: critique-composition\n3: description: Critique a screen's composition — balance, whitespace, rhythm, and gestalt principles.\n4: ---\n5: # Critique Composition\n6: You are an expert in visual composition and gestalt-based design critique.\n7: ## What You Do\n8: You analyse the spatial and structural qualities of a screen: how elements are balanced across the canvas, how whitespace is used to create breathing room and focus, how rhythmic repetition creates coherence, and how gestalt principles are (or aren't) applied. You flag compositional weaknesses and propose specific fixes.\n9: ## Critique Dimensions\n10: ### Balance\n11: Evaluate the distribution of visual weight across the layout.\n12: - Is the composition symmetrically or asymmetrically balanced? Is the choice intentional?\n13: - Are heavy elements (dark fills, large images, dense text blocks) offset by lighter ones?\n14: - Does the layout feel stable, or does it tip — top-heavy, bottom-heavy, left-leaning?\n15: - Is there a clear visual centre of gravity?\n16: ### Whitespace\n17: Evaluate the use of negative space as an active design element.\n18: - Is there sufficient macro whitespace between major sections?\n19: - Is micro whitespace (between labels, icons, and adjacent elements) consistent?\n20: - Does whitespace guide attention, or does it fragment the layout into disconnected areas?\n21: - Are any areas over-compressed or padded inconsistently?\n22: ### Rhythm\n23: Evaluate repetition, pattern, and visual cadence across the screen.\n24: - Are spacing intervals consistent and derived from a spacing scale?\n25: - Do repeated elements (cards, list items, form rows) maintain uniform sizing and gaps?\n26: - Is there visual variety without chaos — a balance of repetition and differentiation?\n27: - Do section breaks and dividers create a legible page cadence?\n28: ### Gestalt Principles\n29: Evaluate how the layout exploits perceptual grouping.\n30: - **Proximity**: Are related elements close together? Are unrelated elements clearly separated?\n31: - **Similarity**: Do elements that share a function share a visual treatment?\n32: - **Figure/Ground**: Is the foreground content clearly distinct from the background?\n33: - **Continuity**: Do alignment and flow lines lead the eye smoothly through the composition?\n34: - **Closure**: Are incomplete shapes or groups still perceived correctly?\n35: ## Output Format\n36: For each dimension — Balance, Whitespace, Rhythm, Gestalt — provide:\n37: 1. **Observation** — what you see (neutral, factual)\n38: 2. **Problem** — what is broken and why it matters\n39: 3. **Fix** — a specific, actionable change\n40: Rate each dimension: `pass` / `minor issue` / `major issue`.\n41: ## Common Failure Patterns\n42: - Equal-weight two-column layout with no clear primary/secondary split\n43: - Inconsistent padding — some components use 16px, others 20px or 24px with no system\n44: - Orphaned elements that float without proximity to their related group\n45: - Overcrowded sections adjacent to empty ones, creating unintentional visual cliffs\n46: - Competing horizontal rules and dividers that multiply without adding structure\n\n(End of file - total 46 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\nname: critique-composition\ndescription: Critique a screen's composition — balance, whitespace, rhythm, and gestalt principles.\n---\n# Critique Composition\nYou are an expert in visual composition and gestalt-based design critique.\n## What You Do\nYou analyse the spatial and structural qualities of a screen: how elements are balanced across the canvas, how whitespace is used to create breathing room and focus, how rhythmic repetition creates coherence, and how gestalt principles are (or aren't) applied. You flag compositional weaknesses and propose specific fixes.\n## Critique Dimensions\n### Balance\nEvaluate the distribution of visual weight across the layout.\n- Is the composition symmetrically or asymmetrically balanced? Is the choice intentional?\n- Are heavy elements (dark fills, large images, dense text blocks) offset by lighter ones?\n- Does the layout feel stable, or does it tip — top-heavy, bottom-heavy, left-leaning?\n- Is there a clear visual centre of gravity?\n### Whitespace\nEvaluate the use of negative space as an active design element.\n- Is there sufficient macro whitespace between major sections?\n- Is micro whitespace (between labels, icons, and adjacent elements) consistent?\n- Does whitespace guide attention, or does it fragment the layout into disconnected areas?","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/visual-critique/skills/critique-composition/SKILL.md","text":"---\nname: critique-composition\ndescription: Critique a screen's composition — balance, whitespace, rhythm, and gestalt principles.\n---\n# Critique Composition\nYou are an expert in visual composition and gestalt-based design critique.\n## What You Do\nYou analyse the spatial and structural qualities of a screen: how elements are balanced across the canvas, how whitespace is used to create breathing room and focus, how rhythmic repetition creates coherence, and how gestalt principles are (or aren't) applied. You flag compositional weaknesses and propose specific fixes.\n## Critique Dimensions\n### Balance\nEvaluate the distribution of visual weight across the layout.\n- Is the composition symmetrically or asymmetrically balanced? Is the choice intentional?\n- Are heavy elements (dark fills, large images, dense text blocks) offset by lighter ones?\n- Does the layout feel stable, or does it tip — top-heavy, bottom-heavy, left-leaning?\n- Is there a clear visual centre of gravity?\n### Whitespace\nEvaluate the use of negative space as an active design element.\n- Is there sufficient macro whitespace between major sections?\n- Is micro whitespace (between labels, icons, and adjacent elements) consistent?\n- Does whitespace guide attention, or does it fragment the layout into disconnected areas?\n- Are any areas over-compressed or padded inconsistently?\n### Rhythm\nEvaluate repetition, pattern, and visual cadence across the screen.\n- Are spacing intervals consistent and derived from a spacing scale?\n- Do repeated elements (cards, list items, form rows) maintain uniform sizing and gaps?\n- Is there visual variety without chaos — a balance of repetition and differentiation?\n- Do section breaks and dividers create a legible page cadence?\n### Gestalt Principles\nEvaluate how the layout exploits perceptual grouping.\n- **Proximity**: Are related elements close together? Are unrelated elements clearly separated?\n- **Similarity**: Do elements that share a function share a visual treatment?\n- **Figure/Ground**: Is the foreground content clearly distinct from the background?\n- **Continuity**: Do alignment and flow lines lead the eye smoothly through the composition?\n- **Closure**: Are incomplete shapes or groups still perceived correctly?\n## Output Format\nFor each dimension — Balance, Whitespace, Rhythm, Gestalt — provide:\n1. **Observation** — what you see (neutral, factual)\n2. **Problem** — what is broken and why it matters\n3. **Fix** — a specific, actionable change\nRate each dimension: `pass` / `minor issue` / `major issue`.\n## Common Failure Patterns\n- Equal-weight two-column layout with no clear primary/secondary split\n- Inconsistent padding — some components use 16px, others 20px or 24px with no system\n- Orphaned elements that float without proximity to their related group\n- Overcrowded sections adjacent to empty ones, creating unintentional visual cliffs\n- Competing horizontal rules and dividers that multiply without adding structure","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":46,"totalLines":46,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/visual-critique/skills/critique-composition/SKILL.md","time":{"start":1782382764899,"end":1782382764913}},"id":"prt_efe4a9d810016mj3Ss6NEW4tka","sessionID":"ses_101b8caf5ffeN4H3YS4hZhe6E8","messageID":"msg_efe4a61d0001rA4rYg3cesNpIr"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782382766472,"sessionID":"ses_101b8caf5ffeN4H3YS4hZhe6E8","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"tool_wrMV8iJztxvI6JZkWEW4Z5U0","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/ux-strategy/skills/design-brief/SKILL.md","limit":80},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/ux-strategy/skills/design-brief/SKILL.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: name: design-brief\n3: description: Write a comprehensive design brief that defines the problem space, constraints, audience, and success criteria.\n4: ---\n5: # Design Brief\n6: You are an expert in writing design briefs that set teams up for focused, effective work.\n7: ## What You Do\n8: You create briefs defining problem, audience, constraints, and success criteria.\n9: ## Brief Structure\n10: 1. **Project Overview** — Name, summary, business context, stakeholder\n11: 2. **Problem Statement** — What, who, evidence, consequences\n12: 3. **Target Audience** — Primary/secondary users, characteristics, personas\n13: 4. **Goals and Success Criteria** — Design goal, metrics, qualitative indicators\n14: 5. **Scope and Constraints** — In/out of scope, technical/brand/timeline/legal\n15: 6. **Context and Inputs** — Research, competitive refs, previous attempts\n16: 7. **Deliverables and Timeline** — Outputs, milestones, review points, deadline\n17: ## Best Practices\n18: - Concise but complete\n19: - Focus on problem, not predetermined solution\n20: - Include measurable success criteria\n21: - Get stakeholder sign-off before starting\n22: - Reference throughout the project\n\n(End of file - total 22 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\nname: design-brief\ndescription: Write a comprehensive design brief that defines the problem space, constraints, audience, and success criteria.\n---\n# Design Brief\nYou are an expert in writing design briefs that set teams up for focused, effective work.\n## What You Do\nYou create briefs defining problem, audience, constraints, and success criteria.\n## Brief Structure\n1. **Project Overview** — Name, summary, business context, stakeholder\n2. **Problem Statement** — What, who, evidence, consequences\n3. **Target Audience** — Primary/secondary users, characteristics, personas\n4. **Goals and Success Criteria** — Design goal, metrics, qualitative indicators\n5. **Scope and Constraints** — In/out of scope, technical/brand/timeline/legal\n6. **Context and Inputs** — Research, competitive refs, previous attempts\n7. **Deliverables and Timeline** — Outputs, milestones, review points, deadline\n## Best Practices\n- Concise but complete\n- Focus on problem, not predetermined solution\n- Include measurable success criteria","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/ux-strategy/skills/design-brief/SKILL.md","text":"---\nname: design-brief\ndescription: Write a comprehensive design brief that defines the problem space, constraints, audience, and success criteria.\n---\n# Design Brief\nYou are an expert in writing design briefs that set teams up for focused, effective work.\n## What You Do\nYou create briefs defining problem, audience, constraints, and success criteria.\n## Brief Structure\n1. **Project Overview** — Name, summary, business context, stakeholder\n2. **Problem Statement** — What, who, evidence, consequences\n3. **Target Audience** — Primary/secondary users, characteristics, personas\n4. **Goals and Success Criteria** — Design goal, metrics, qualitative indicators\n5. **Scope and Constraints** — In/out of scope, technical/brand/timeline/legal\n6. **Context and Inputs** — Research, competitive refs, previous attempts\n7. **Deliverables and Timeline** — Outputs, milestones, review points, deadline\n## Best Practices\n- Concise but complete\n- Focus on problem, not predetermined solution\n- Include measurable success criteria\n- Get stakeholder sign-off before starting\n- Reference throughout the project","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":22,"totalLines":22,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/ux-strategy/skills/design-brief/SKILL.md","time":{"start":1782382766450,"end":1782382766470}},"id":"prt_efe4aa369001ZzNJ2xhOUrZ119","sessionID":"ses_101b8caf5ffeN4H3YS4hZhe6E8","messageID":"msg_efe4a61d0001rA4rYg3cesNpIr"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782382767569,"sessionID":"ses_101b8caf5ffeN4H3YS4hZhe6E8","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"tool_hQRBu4TsbesMLr6eaS2I5lkR","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/design-systems/skills/design-token/SKILL.md","limit":80},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/design-systems/skills/design-token/SKILL.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: name: design-token\n3: description: Define and organize design tokens (color, spacing, typography, elevation) with naming conventions and usage guidance.\n4: ---\n5: # Design Token\n6: You are an expert in design token architecture and systematic design foundations.\n7: ## What You Do\n8: You help define, organize, and document design tokens — the atomic values that drive visual consistency. You understand token taxonomies, naming hierarchies, and cross-platform mapping.\n9: ## Token Categories\n10: - **Color**: Global palette, alias tokens (surface, text, border), component tokens\n11: - **Spacing**: Base unit (4px/8px), scale (xs through 3xl), contextual (inset, stack, inline)\n12: - **Typography**: Font families, size scale, weights, line heights\n13: - **Elevation**: Shadow levels, z-index scale\n14: - **Border**: Radius scale, width scale, style options\n15: - **Motion**: Duration scale, easing functions\n16: ## Token Tiers\n17: 1. **Global tokens** — Raw values (e.g., blue-500: #3B82F6)\n18: 2. **Alias tokens** — Semantic references (e.g., color-action-primary)\n19: 3. **Component tokens** — Scoped usage (e.g., button-color-primary)\n20: ## Naming Convention\n21: Pattern: {category}-{property}-{variant}-{state}\n22: ## Best Practices\n23: - Start with global tokens, then create semantic aliases\n24: - Never reference raw values in components\n25: - Document each token with usage context\n26: - Version tokens alongside your design system\n27: - Support theming by keeping alias tokens abstract\n\n(End of file - total 27 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\nname: design-token\ndescription: Define and organize design tokens (color, spacing, typography, elevation) with naming conventions and usage guidance.\n---\n# Design Token\nYou are an expert in design token architecture and systematic design foundations.\n## What You Do\nYou help define, organize, and document design tokens — the atomic values that drive visual consistency. You understand token taxonomies, naming hierarchies, and cross-platform mapping.\n## Token Categories\n- **Color**: Global palette, alias tokens (surface, text, border), component tokens\n- **Spacing**: Base unit (4px/8px), scale (xs through 3xl), contextual (inset, stack, inline)\n- **Typography**: Font families, size scale, weights, line heights\n- **Elevation**: Shadow levels, z-index scale\n- **Border**: Radius scale, width scale, style options\n- **Motion**: Duration scale, easing functions\n## Token Tiers\n1. **Global tokens** — Raw values (e.g., blue-500: #3B82F6)\n2. **Alias tokens** — Semantic references (e.g., color-action-primary)\n3. **Component tokens** — Scoped usage (e.g., button-color-primary)\n## Naming Convention","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/design-systems/skills/design-token/SKILL.md","text":"---\nname: design-token\ndescription: Define and organize design tokens (color, spacing, typography, elevation) with naming conventions and usage guidance.\n---\n# Design Token\nYou are an expert in design token architecture and systematic design foundations.\n## What You Do\nYou help define, organize, and document design tokens — the atomic values that drive visual consistency. You understand token taxonomies, naming hierarchies, and cross-platform mapping.\n## Token Categories\n- **Color**: Global palette, alias tokens (surface, text, border), component tokens\n- **Spacing**: Base unit (4px/8px), scale (xs through 3xl), contextual (inset, stack, inline)\n- **Typography**: Font families, size scale, weights, line heights\n- **Elevation**: Shadow levels, z-index scale\n- **Border**: Radius scale, width scale, style options\n- **Motion**: Duration scale, easing functions\n## Token Tiers\n1. **Global tokens** — Raw values (e.g., blue-500: #3B82F6)\n2. **Alias tokens** — Semantic references (e.g., color-action-primary)\n3. **Component tokens** — Scoped usage (e.g., button-color-primary)\n## Naming Convention\nPattern: {category}-{property}-{variant}-{state}\n## Best Practices\n- Start with global tokens, then create semantic aliases\n- Never reference raw values in components\n- Document each token with usage context\n- Version tokens alongside your design system\n- Support theming by keeping alias tokens abstract","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":27,"totalLines":27,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/design-systems/skills/design-token/SKILL.md","time":{"start":1782382767557,"end":1782382767567}},"id":"prt_efe4aa976001VKrh8fVIjhOnnm","sessionID":"ses_101b8caf5ffeN4H3YS4hZhe6E8","messageID":"msg_efe4a61d0001rA4rYg3cesNpIr"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782382768922,"sessionID":"ses_101b8caf5ffeN4H3YS4hZhe6E8","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"tool_BTV2oPYaIWV995pgGxMEuXKA","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/design-research/skills/user-persona/SKILL.md","limit":80},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/design-research/skills/user-persona/SKILL.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: name: user-persona\n3: description: Create refined user personas from research data with demographics, goals, frustrations, and behavioral patterns. Use when synthesizing user research into actionable persona profiles for design decisions.\n4: ---\n5: \n6: # User Persona\n7: \n8: Create comprehensive user personas grounded in research data for product and UX design.\n9: \n10: ## Context\n11: \n12: You are a senior UX researcher helping a design team create user personas for $ARGUMENTS. If the user provides files (research data, interview transcripts, survey results, analytics), read them first. If they mention a product URL, use web search to understand the product.\n13: \n14: ## Domain Context\n15: \n16: - Personas (Alan Cooper, About Face): Archetypical users based on behavioral patterns, not demographics alone.\n17: - Each persona should feel like a real person the team can empathize with and design for.\n18: - Personas should be grounded in actual research data, not assumptions.\n19: - Include behavioral variables, goals (life goals, experience goals, end goals), and frustrations.\n20: \n21: ## Instructions\n22: \n23: The user will describe their product and available research data. Work through these steps:\n24: \n25: 1. **Gather inputs**: Confirm the product, target audience, and available research data. Ask for clarification if anything is ambiguous.\n26: 2. **Identify behavioral patterns**: Analyze the research data to find clusters of behaviors, motivations, and needs.\n27: 3. **Define 2-4 personas** — for each persona, include:\n28:    - Name, photo description, and a one-line quote that captures their mindset\n29:    - Demographics: age range, occupation, tech comfort, relevant context\n30:    - Goals: what they want to achieve (functional, emotional, social)\n31:    - Frustrations: current pain points and unmet needs\n32:    - Behaviors: how they currently approach the problem\n33:    - Scenario: a brief day-in-the-life narrative\n34:    - Design implications: what this means for product decisions\n35: 4. **Prioritize**: Identify the primary persona (the one the design must satisfy first) and explain why.\n36: 5. **Highlight gaps**: Note any research gaps that would strengthen the personas.\n37: 6. Think step by step. Present personas in a clear, structured format. If the output is substantial, save it as a markdown document in the user's workspace.\n38: \n39: ## Further Reading\n40: \n41: - About Face — Alan Cooper\n42: - Lean UX — Jeff Gothelf and Josh Seiden\n43: - Just Enough Research — Erika Hall\n\n(End of file - total 43 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\nname: user-persona\ndescription: Create refined user personas from research data with demographics, goals, frustrations, and behavioral patterns. Use when synthesizing user research into actionable persona profiles for design decisions.\n---\n\n# User Persona\n\nCreate comprehensive user personas grounded in research data for product and UX design.\n\n## Context\n\nYou are a senior UX researcher helping a design team create user personas for $ARGUMENTS. If the user provides files (research data, interview transcripts, survey results, analytics), read them first. If they mention a product URL, use web search to understand the product.\n\n## Domain Context\n\n- Personas (Alan Cooper, About Face): Archetypical users based on behavioral patterns, not demographics alone.\n- Each persona should feel like a real person the team can empathize with and design for.\n- Personas should be grounded in actual research data, not assumptions.\n- Include behavioral variables, goals (life goals, experience goals, end goals), and frustrations.\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/design-research/skills/user-persona/SKILL.md","text":"---\nname: user-persona\ndescription: Create refined user personas from research data with demographics, goals, frustrations, and behavioral patterns. Use when synthesizing user research into actionable persona profiles for design decisions.\n---\n\n# User Persona\n\nCreate comprehensive user personas grounded in research data for product and UX design.\n\n## Context\n\nYou are a senior UX researcher helping a design team create user personas for $ARGUMENTS. If the user provides files (research data, interview transcripts, survey results, analytics), read them first. If they mention a product URL, use web search to understand the product.\n\n## Domain Context\n\n- Personas (Alan Cooper, About Face): Archetypical users based on behavioral patterns, not demographics alone.\n- Each persona should feel like a real person the team can empathize with and design for.\n- Personas should be grounded in actual research data, not assumptions.\n- Include behavioral variables, goals (life goals, experience goals, end goals), and frustrations.\n\n## Instructions\n\nThe user will describe their product and available research data. Work through these steps:\n\n1. **Gather inputs**: Confirm the product, target audience, and available research data. Ask for clarification if anything is ambiguous.\n2. **Identify behavioral patterns**: Analyze the research data to find clusters of behaviors, motivations, and needs.\n3. **Define 2-4 personas** — for each persona, include:\n   - Name, photo description, and a one-line quote that captures their mindset\n   - Demographics: age range, occupation, tech comfort, relevant context\n   - Goals: what they want to achieve (functional, emotional, social)\n   - Frustrations: current pain points and unmet needs\n   - Behaviors: how they currently approach the problem\n   - Scenario: a brief day-in-the-life narrative\n   - Design implications: what this means for product decisions\n4. **Prioritize**: Identify the primary persona (the one the design must satisfy first) and explain why.\n5. **Highlight gaps**: Note any research gaps that would strengthen the personas.\n6. Think step by step. Present personas in a clear, structured format. If the output is substantial, save it as a markdown document in the user's workspace.\n\n## Further Reading\n\n- About Face — Alan Cooper\n- Lean UX — Jeff Gothelf and Josh Seiden\n- Just Enough Research — Erika Hall","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":43,"totalLines":43,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/design-research/skills/user-persona/SKILL.md","time":{"start":1782382768913,"end":1782382768921}},"id":"prt_efe4aadc7001Z36eGPzmvTliTj","sessionID":"ses_101b8caf5ffeN4H3YS4hZhe6E8","messageID":"msg_efe4a61d0001rA4rYg3cesNpIr"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782382769889,"sessionID":"ses_101b8caf5ffeN4H3YS4hZhe6E8","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"tool_9L5DhUfQfKClMLO0n5J5nLsl","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/designer-toolkit/skills/ux-writing/SKILL.md","limit":80},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/designer-toolkit/skills/ux-writing/SKILL.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: name: ux-writing\n3: description: Write effective UI copy including microcopy, error messages, empty states, and CTAs.\n4: ---\n5: # UX Writing\n6: You are an expert in writing clear, helpful interface copy that guides users and reinforces the product voice.\n7: ## What You Do\n8: You write UI copy that helps users accomplish tasks, understand status, and feel confident.\n9: ## UX Writing Categories\n10: ### Microcopy\n11: - Button labels: action-oriented, specific (not just 'Submit')\n12: - Form labels: clear, concise, no jargon\n13: - Tooltips: brief explanations for complex features\n14: - Placeholder text: example format, not instructions\n15: ### Error Messages\n16: - Say what happened (clear, not technical)\n17: - Say why (if helpful and brief)\n18: - Say what to do next (specific action)\n19: - Use a human tone (not robotic or blaming)\n20: ### Empty States\n21: - Explain what will appear here\n22: - Guide the user to take action\n23: - Use an encouraging, helpful tone\n24: - Provide a clear CTA\n25: ### Confirmation Messages\n26: - Confirm what just happened\n27: - Provide next steps if relevant\n28: - Include undo option for reversible actions\n29: - Keep it brief and positive\n30: ### Onboarding Copy\n31: - Welcome without overwhelming\n32: - One concept at a time\n33: - Action-oriented (do, not just read)\n34: - Allow skipping\n35: ### CTAs (Calls to Action)\n36: - Start with a verb\n37: - Be specific about the outcome\n38: - Match user intent (not business intent)\n39: - Primary CTA should be the most common action\n40: ## Voice and Tone Guidelines\n41: - **Voice** (consistent): brand personality, vocabulary, perspective\n42: - **Tone** (varies): adapts to context (celebration vs error vs instruction)\n43: ## Writing Principles\n44: - Clear over clever\n45: - Concise over comprehensive\n46: - Helpful over promotional\n47: - Consistent over creative\n48: - Inclusive over casual\n49: ## Best Practices\n50: - Write copy before designing the UI (content-first)\n51: - Test copy with real users\n52: - Create a terminology dictionary\n53: - Avoid jargon, abbreviations, and idioms\n54: - Consider translation and localization from the start\n\n(End of file - total 54 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\nname: ux-writing\ndescription: Write effective UI copy including microcopy, error messages, empty states, and CTAs.\n---\n# UX Writing\nYou are an expert in writing clear, helpful interface copy that guides users and reinforces the product voice.\n## What You Do\nYou write UI copy that helps users accomplish tasks, understand status, and feel confident.\n## UX Writing Categories\n### Microcopy\n- Button labels: action-oriented, specific (not just 'Submit')\n- Form labels: clear, concise, no jargon\n- Tooltips: brief explanations for complex features\n- Placeholder text: example format, not instructions\n### Error Messages\n- Say what happened (clear, not technical)\n- Say why (if helpful and brief)\n- Say what to do next (specific action)\n- Use a human tone (not robotic or blaming)\n### Empty States","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/designer-toolkit/skills/ux-writing/SKILL.md","text":"---\nname: ux-writing\ndescription: Write effective UI copy including microcopy, error messages, empty states, and CTAs.\n---\n# UX Writing\nYou are an expert in writing clear, helpful interface copy that guides users and reinforces the product voice.\n## What You Do\nYou write UI copy that helps users accomplish tasks, understand status, and feel confident.\n## UX Writing Categories\n### Microcopy\n- Button labels: action-oriented, specific (not just 'Submit')\n- Form labels: clear, concise, no jargon\n- Tooltips: brief explanations for complex features\n- Placeholder text: example format, not instructions\n### Error Messages\n- Say what happened (clear, not technical)\n- Say why (if helpful and brief)\n- Say what to do next (specific action)\n- Use a human tone (not robotic or blaming)\n### Empty States\n- Explain what will appear here\n- Guide the user to take action\n- Use an encouraging, helpful tone\n- Provide a clear CTA\n### Confirmation Messages\n- Confirm what just happened\n- Provide next steps if relevant\n- Include undo option for reversible actions\n- Keep it brief and positive\n### Onboarding Copy\n- Welcome without overwhelming\n- One concept at a time\n- Action-oriented (do, not just read)\n- Allow skipping\n### CTAs (Calls to Action)\n- Start with a verb\n- Be specific about the outcome\n- Match user intent (not business intent)\n- Primary CTA should be the most common action\n## Voice and Tone Guidelines\n- **Voice** (consistent): brand personality, vocabulary, perspective\n- **Tone** (varies): adapts to context (celebration vs error vs instruction)\n## Writing Principles\n- Clear over clever\n- Concise over comprehensive\n- Helpful over promotional\n- Consistent over creative\n- Inclusive over casual\n## Best Practices\n- Write copy before designing the UI (content-first)\n- Test copy with real users\n- Create a terminology dictionary\n- Avoid jargon, abbreviations, and idioms\n- Consider translation and localization from the start","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":54,"totalLines":54,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/designer-toolkit/skills/ux-writing/SKILL.md","time":{"start":1782382769882,"end":1782382769887}},"id":"prt_efe4ab313001iI9q5zF49gPCGD","sessionID":"ses_101b8caf5ffeN4H3YS4hZhe6E8","messageID":"msg_efe4a61d0001rA4rYg3cesNpIr"}}
